Having easy access to a vdw representation would be nice. Like `add_vdw`. I currently need to manually set the representation. Example and picture below. (protein is 1E8L)

```
v.representations = [
    {"type": "spacefill", "params": {
        "radiusType": 'vdw',
    }}
]
```

![screenshot 1](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4302678/18880762/4e554ab2-84d9-11e6-82c9-378b946e5d07.png)


I would also be interested in a general `add_ball` method to only show balls of a specific radius. See example below. That is great to visualize some coarse grained models vy some software (e.g. [HYDROPRO](http://leonardo.inf.um.es/macromol/programs/hydropro/hydropro.htm) )

```
view.representations = [
    {"type": "spacefill", "params": {
        "radiusType": 'size',
        "radius": 4.2
    }}
]
```

![screenshot](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4302678/18880607/bed383e0-84d8-11e6-9b41-73de0d594e3e.png)

Provider CloudNS fails to authenticate when using auth-id for authentication, rather than auth-subid or auth-subuser.

Line 146 in lexicon/providers/cloudns.py  reads `if self.is_given_option(self.options['auth_id']):`. It should instead should read `if self.is_given_option('auth_id'):`.

I've inlined a patch below which fixes this. Apologies if patch sets are not your preferred workflow.

    --- cloudns.py
    +++ cloudns.pr203fix.py
    @@ -143,7 +143,7 @@ 
             if not self.options['auth_password']:
                 raise Exception('No valid authentication data passed, expected: auth-password')
    
    -        if self._is_given_option(self.options['auth_id']):
    +        if self._is_given_option('auth_id'):
                 return {'auth-id': self.options['auth_id'], 'auth-password': self.options['auth_password']}
             elif self._is_given_option('auth_subid'):
                 return {'sub-auth-id': self.options['auth_subid'], 'auth-password': self.options['auth_password']}

https://www.englishclub.com/vocabulary/time-telling-time.htm

```
#!/usr/bin/env bash

# I made this. meme.
# -lasers 12/23/2016

DATE="$(date '+%H%M%p')"
H="${DATE:0:2}"
M="${DATE:2:2}"
H="${H#0}"
M="${M#0}"
CH=''
CM=''

declare -a NUM=([oclock]="o'clock" [oh]='oh' [1]='one' [2]='two' [3]='three'
[4]='four' [5]='five' [6]='six' [7]='seven' [8]='eight' [9]='nine' [10]='ten'
[11]='eleven' [12]='twelve' [13]='thirteen' [14]='fourteen' [15]='fifteen'
[16]='sixteen' [17]='seventeen' [18]='eighteen' [19]='ninteen' [20]='twenty'
[30]='thirty' [40]='fourty' [50]='fifty')

addDigit(){ [[ $1 -ne 0 ]] && CM+=-${NUM[$1]} ; }

case $M in
    [1-9]) CM=${NUM[oh]} ; addDigit ${M} ;;
    1[0-9]) CM=${NUM[$M]} ;;
    2[0-9]) CM=${NUM[20]} ; addDigit ${M#2} ;;
    3[0-9]) CM=${NUM[30]} ; addDigit ${M#3} ;;
    4[0-9]) CM=${NUM[40]} ; addDigit ${M#4} ;;
    5[0-9]) CM=${NUM[50]} ; addDigit ${M#5} ;;
    0) CM=${NUM[oclock]} ;;
esac
case $H in
    [1-9]|1[0-2]) CH=${NUM[$H]} ;;
    1[3-9]|2[0-3]) CH=${NUM[$H-12]} ;;
    0) CH=${NUM[12]} ;;
esac
case $DATE in
    '1200AM') echo 'midnight' ;;
    '1200PM') echo 'afternoon' ;;
    *) echo "$CH $CM"
esac
```

a `config.max_depth` should not be changed when it's passed to `pp` along with a different `max_depth`.

Example:
```python
>>> from beeprint import pp, Config
>>> a = {
    'apple': 'banana',
    'dict': {
        'key': 'value'
    }
}
>>> cfg = Config()
>>> pp(a, config=cfg)
{
  'apple': 'banana',
  'dict': {
    'key': 'value',
  },
}
>>> pp(a, config=cfg, max_depth=1)
{
  'apple': 'banana',
  'dict': {'key': 'value'},
}
>>> pp(a, config=cfg)
{
  'apple': 'banana',
  'dict': {'key': 'value'},
}
```

