This issue is discovered when i tried to add statistics from pr_curve_streaming_ops to the dict of eval_metric_ops in tf.estimator.EstimatorSpec.

Running evaluate causes the following warning to be displayed. But I am able to retrieve the eval output directly from tf.Estimator.evaluate and it appears that the protobuf serialization is working.
```python
res = model.evaluate(...)
summary_pb2.Summary.FromString(res['PR_0'])
# output
WARNING:tensorflow:Skipping summary for PR_0, must be a float, np.float32, np.int64, np.int32 or int or a serialized string of Summary.
value {
  tag: "PR_0/pr_curves"
  tensor {
    dtype: DT_FLOAT
    tensor_shape {
      dim {
        size: 6
      }
      dim {
        size: 201
      }
    }
...
}
```

Checking the content of the file and tensorboard shows that the protobuf data is missing:
```python
from tensorboard.backend.event_processing.event_file_loader import EventFileLoader
eval_loader = EventFileLoader('/tmp/nkm/resPool003551/eval/events.out.tfevents.1518280897.dev15-wslpt')
eval_events = list(eval_loader.Load())
eval_events[3]
# output
wall_time: 1518280897.7904496
step: 3923
summary {
  value {
    tag: "eval_mean_accuracy"
    simple_value: 0.2056954801082611
  }
  value {
    tag: "loss"
    simple_value: 911411.1875
  }
}
```
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17044118/36063759-17181570-0ebc-11e8-99f2-693381cab81c.png)


After some further digging, it appears that the culprit lies in the string type check in tf.estimator.estimator._write_dict_to_summary: https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/16fabd1fc3408252d816bf53698df8f05c9ee304/tensorflow/python/estimator/estimator.py#L1106

protobuf.SerializeToString in python 3 returns bytes instead of string. As such, the type check will cause all protobuf serialized stats to fail during estimator.evaluate for python3. To have a version compatible fix, we will probably need a `if (py2 and isinstance(data, str)) or (py3 and isinstance(data, bytes))` check instead, six can't save us here =(

I'm new to this github but do let me know if this issue should be moved over to tensorflow instead.

#### Issue description
TL;DR: When accessing and modiyfing a singleton class through python scripts evaluated with py::eval, Ubuntu (14/16) maintains a single object between the C++ and Python layer, while Windows appears to duplicate the object.

I have a singleton class that I have wrapped with pybind.  I am also trying trying to access and modify this class through the pybind interpreter.  Since I want to support arbitrary code execution of scripts and files I am using py::eval.  Say I have modified the singleton class in C++, then later call py::eval on a script that accesses this singleton class. On Ubuntu, the same singleton object is shared between the C++ and Python layer, and changes to the object are shared.  On Windows, no changes persist between the layers.

Given the code below, the output on Ubuntu is:
```
C++: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 3
C++: Foo is 3
```
And on Windows 
```
C++: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 0
Python: Foo is 3
C++: Foo is 2
```

I have tried Python 2.7 and 3.4 on Windows.  And 2.7, 3.4, 3.4, 3.6 on Ubuntu.  For compiling on Windows I have tried MSVC 2015 and 2017.  On Ubuntu I have tried gcc 5.x and 6.x.  The results have been the same.  I am under the assumption this is an issue with how libraries are being loaded, and how that is handled differently between the two operating systems.  However I don't have much more to go on than that.  Is there an obvious mistake being made here?  If not is there a direction I can explore to work on resolving this?

#### Reproducible example code

main.cpp
```
#include <pybind11/embed.h>
#include "Foo.h"
#include <iostream>
namespace py = pybind11;
using namespace std;
int main() {
	py::scoped_interpreter guard{};
	Foo::get().setVal(2);
	cout << "C++: Foo is " << Foo::get().getVal() << endl;
	py::object globals = py::module::import("__main__").attr("__dict__");
	py::object locals = py::dict();
	py::eval<py::eval_statements>(R"(
				import Foo_Py
				print('Python: Foo is ' + str(Foo_Py.Foo.get().getValue()))
				Foo_Py.Foo.get().setValue(3)
				print('Python: Foo is ' + str(Foo_Py.Foo.get().getValue()))

			)", globals, locals);

	cout << "C++: Foo is " << Foo::get().getVal() << endl;
}
```
Foo_Py.cpp
```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include "Foo.h"
#include <memory>
using namespace std;
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(Foo_Py) {
	py::module m("Foo_Py");
	py::class_<Foo, unique_ptr<Foo, py::nodelete>>(m, "Foo")
		.def_static("get", &Foo::get, py::return_value_policy::reference)
		.def("getValue", &Foo::getVal)
		.def("setValue", &Foo::setVal);

	return m.ptr();
}

```
